<subSubSection id="CE97657EFF8CFFA1FF0E36E4FD0DF898" lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="18" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="863236F5FF8CFFA0FF0E36E4FEDBF819" blockId="16.[151,1436,1699,1996]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis id="B4F9EAE7FF8CFFA0FF0E36E4FE82F968" bold="true" box="[151,279,1699,1725]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Species of 
<taxonomicName id="418D4D76FF8CFFA0FE0536E3FDBDF968" authorityName="Peters" authorityYear="1881" box="[412,552,1700,1725]" class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" genus="Siagonodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B4F9EAE7FF8CFFA0FE0536E3FDBDF968" box="[412,552,1700,1725]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Siagonodon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have 14 midbody scale rows, 10–14 midtail scale rows, 206–289 middorsal scale rows, 8–20 subcaudals, two supralabials, small or moderate or large anterior supralabials, 
<quantity id="41759B10FF8CFFA0FA99368DFA0EF931" box="[1280,1435,1738,1764]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.51" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="2.02" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" unit="mm" value="251.0" valueMax="300.0" valueMin="202.0">202–300 mm</quantity>
maximum adult total length, a body shape of 39–130 (total length/width), a relative tail length of 2.1–6.6%, a tail shape of 1.3–2.6, striped pattern, multiple dorsal colors, and white venter (Table 2). They also lack a supraocular scale. The absence of a supraocular scale distinguishes this genus from the other genus in the subtribe, 
<taxonomicName id="418D4D76FF8CFFA0FE9F3722FECEF8AB" authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1845" box="[262,347,1893,1918]" class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" genus="Epictia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B4F9EAE7FF8CFFA0FE9F3722FECEF8AB" box="[262,347,1893,1918]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Epictia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(except 
<taxonomicName id="418D4D76FF8CFFA0FE5A3722FDACF8AB" authorityName="Taylor" authorityYear="1940" box="[451,569,1893,1918]" class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" genus="Leptotyphlops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nasalis">
<emphasis id="B4F9EAE7FF8CFFA0FE5A3722FDACF8AB" box="[451,569,1893,1918]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">E. nasalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Other traits distinguishing the two genera show overlap, but species of 
<taxonomicName id="418D4D76FF8CFFA0FF0E37CBFEB6F870" authorityName="Peters" authorityYear="1881" box="[151,291,1932,1957]" class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" genus="Siagonodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B4F9EAE7FF8CFFA0FF0E37CBFEB6F870" box="[151,291,1932,1957]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Siagonodon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
tend to have fewer midtail scale rows and a white venter (Table 2). Only one species of this genus was sequenced.
</paragraph>
<caption id="D2F2667DFF8DFFA1FF0E3607FCF4F8D1" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" startId="17.[151,255,1600,1624]" targetBox="[151,1436,194,1576]" targetPageId="17">
<paragraph id="863236F5FF8DFFA1FF0E3607FCF4F8D1" blockId="17.[151,1437,1600,1797]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis id="B4F9EAE7FF8DFFA1FF0E3607FE8FF98D" bold="true" box="[151,282,1600,1624]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">FIGURE 6.</emphasis>
Representatives of the snake Family 
<taxonomicName id="418D4D76FF8DFFA1FD293607FCF8F982" authorityName="Stejneger" authorityYear="1892" box="[688,877,1600,1623]" class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Leptotyphlopidae</taxonomicName>
