<paragraph id="863236F5FF8DFFA1FF5C3775FD0DF898" blockId="17.[151,1436,1842,2023]" box="[197,664,1842,1869]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis id="B4F9EAE7FF8DFFA1FF5C3775FEA4F899" bold="true" box="[197,305,1842,1868]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Content.</emphasis>
Four species (
<tableCitation id="CB0F034EFF8DFFA1FE433774FDA1F898" box="[474,564,1843,1869]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="9.[151,240,151,175]" captionText="TABLE 1. Classification of snakes of the Family Leptotyphlopidae. The arrangement used in this study is compared with that in previous classifications (e.g., McDiarmid et al. 1999; Uetz et al. 2009). Abbreviations for geographic regions are: AR (Arabia), CAF (Central Africa), EAF (East Africa), MAM (Middle America), NAM (North America), SAF (South Africa), SAM (South America), SOC (Socotra Island), SWA (Southwest Asia), WAF (West Africa), and WI (West Indies). Species in bold were sampled in the molecular analyses. Undescribed species used in this study are not listed." pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Table 1</tableCitation>
; 
<figureCitation id="1EB62A70FF8DFFA1FDDA3774FD1CF898" box="[579,649,1843,1869]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="17.[151,255,1600,1624]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,1576]" captionTargetId="figure-168@17.[151,1436,194,1576]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 6. Representatives of the snake Family Leptotyphlopidae from the New World. (A) Epictia albifrons (Brazil, Tocantins, Parque Estadual de Cantão); photograph by Laurie J. Vitt. (B) Epictia alfredschmidti (Peru: Ancash; Malvas); photograph by E. Lehr. (C) Epictia cf. diaplocia (Brazil: Amazonas; Reserva Adolfo Ducke, 30 km N Manaus); photograph by Laurie J. Vitt. (D) Siagonodon brasiliensis (Brazil: Tocantins; Lalapão); photograph by Laurie J. Vitt. (E) Siagonodon septemstriatus (Brazil: Roraima; Fazenda Nova Esperança); photograph by Laurie J. Vitt. (F) Epictia columbi (Bahamas: San Salvador); photograph by S. Blair Hedges." pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="CE97657EFF8DFFA1FF5C371EFC60F84F" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="863236F5FF8DFFA1FF5C371EFC60F84F" blockId="17.[151,1436,1842,2023]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis id="B4F9EAE7FF8DFFA1FF5C371EFEE1F8A6" bold="true" box="[197,372,1881,1907]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Distribution.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="418D4D76FF8DFFA1FEE7371DFD80F8A6" authorityName="Peters" authorityYear="1881" box="[382,533,1882,1907]" class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" genus="Siagonodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B4F9EAE7FF8DFFA1FEE7371DFD80F8A6" box="[382,533,1882,1907]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Siagonodon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distributed east of the Andes in South America, from southeastern 
<collectingCountry id="FE9A7665FF8DFFA1FF0E37C7FE87F84F" box="[151,274,1920,1946]" name="Venezuela" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="FE9A7665FF8DFFA1FE8737C7FEE9F84F" box="[286,380,1920,1946]" name="Guyana" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Guyana</collectingCountry>
, and French Guiana in the north to 
<collectingCountry id="FE9A7665FF8DFFA1FC8337C7FC1AF84F" box="[794,911,1920,1946]" name="Argentina" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Argentina</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="1EB62A70FF8DFFA1FC0637C7FC70F84F" box="[927,997,1920,1946]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="22.[151,264,1647,1671]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,200,1620]" captionTargetId="figure-102@22.[151,1436,197,1624]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURE 8. Distributions of genera of leptotyphlopid snakes in the New World. (A) Epictia. (B) Rena. (C) Siagonodon. (D) Tricheilostoma (South America), Mitophis (Hispaniola), and Tetracheilostoma (Martinique, Saint Lucia, and Barbados). Some islands close to mainland areas are not indicated; see text for description of distribution." pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="CE97657EFF8DFFA1FF5C37E1FB96F832" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="863236F5FF8DFFA1FF5C37E1FB96F832" blockId="17.[151,1436,1842,2023]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis id="B4F9EAE7FF8DFFA1FF5C37E1FEDBF815" bold="true" box="[197,334,1958,1984]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Etymology</emphasis>
. The generic name is masculine and derived from the Greek nouns 
<emphasis id="B4F9EAE7FF8DFFA1FB1237E0FB4EF815" box="[1163,1243,1959,1984]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">siagon</emphasis>
(jaw) and 
<emphasis id="B4F9EAE7FF8DFFA1FAF937E0FA09F815" box="[1376,1436,1959,1984]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">odon</emphasis>
(tooth), probably in allusion to the presence of teeth only on the lower jaw.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="CE97657EFF8EFFA2FF5C30D0FBBFFEF3" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="863236F5FF8EFFA2FF5C30D0FBBFFEF3" blockId="18.[151,1436,151,294]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis id="B4F9EAE7FF8EFFA2FF5C30D0FED4FF64" bold="true" box="[197,321,151,177]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Remarks.</emphasis>
Species placed here in 
<taxonomicName id="418D4D76FF8EFFA2FDFF30DFFD62FF64" authorityName="Peters" authorityYear="1881" box="[614,759,152,177]" class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" genus="Siagonodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B4F9EAE7FF8EFFA2FDFF30DFFD62FF64" box="[614,759,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Siagonodon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
include members of the 
<taxonomicName id="418D4D76FF8EFFA2FBB030DFFB4CFF64" authorityName="SAM" baseAuthorityName="Schneider" baseAuthorityYear="1801" box="[1065,1241,152,177]" class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" genus="Siagonodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="septemstriatus">
<emphasis id="B4F9EAE7FF8EFFA2FBB030DFFB4CFF64" box="[1065,1241,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">septemstriatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Group (Orejas- 
<collectingRegion id="4449F817FF8EFFA2FF0E30F9FF6FFF0D" box="[151,250,190,216]" country="Venezuela" name="Miranda" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Miranda</collectingRegion>
1967; 
<bibRefCitation id="E21C4B04FF8EFFA2FED530F9FE4FFF0D" author="Peters" box="[332,474,190,216]" firstAuthor="Peters" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="1 - 347" refId="ref26544" refString="Peters, J. A. (1970) Catalogue of the Neotropical Squamata: Part 1. Snakes. Bulletin of the United States National Museum, 297, 1 - 347." type="journal article" year="1970">Peters 1970</bibRefCitation>
). Only one representative (
<taxonomicName id="418D4D76FF8EFFA2FC8130F8FC4BFF0D" authorityName="SAM" baseAuthorityName="Schneider" baseAuthorityYear="1801" box="[792,990,191,216]" class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" genus="Siagonodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="septemstriatus">
<emphasis id="B4F9EAE7FF8EFFA2FC8130F8FC4BFF0D" box="[792,990,191,216]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">S. septemstriatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) was included, and it clustered with a monophyletic 
<taxonomicName id="418D4D76FF8EFFA2FEA630A2FE06FF2B" authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1845" box="[319,403,229,254]" class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" genus="Epictia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B4F9EAE7FF8EFFA2FEA630A2FE06FF2B" box="[319,403,229,254]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Epictia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as expected based on character data. However, future molecular studies with additional species are needed to further test the allocation of species to these two genera.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
